defaultPay restraint is an important part of the Government’s strategy to meet the current economic and fiscal challen
defaultges while maintaining services and jobs. The Government has set clear expectations on pay restraint across the public services, with public sector pay awards averaging up to 1% in 2013–14 and 2014–15. The 2013 Budget confirmed that public sector pay awards
default in 2015–16 will be limited to an average of up to 1%, and the 
default2013 S
defaultpending 
defaultReview
default confirmed the cross-government commitment to reducing the cost of progression pay in public services, including the NHS. In the longer term, of course, pay trends will be d
defaultependent on wider economic factors.
