default21
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs the previous section shows, QIPP has so far not met its targets for transformational change, which is vital for the financial sustainability of the NHS in the long term. QIPP savings so far have been weighted towards central actions, includ
defaulting pay and administrative cost reductions and tactical efficiency programmes. The NHS cannot rely on pay restraint and reductions in the unit cost of care to deliver QIPP-scale efficiencies in the
default long term.
default22
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo address this, NHS England has increased the 
defaultsystem’s focus on transformational change.  From 2013
default–14
default onwards, QIPP plans for CCGs and NHS England’s direct commissioners are broken down between transactional schemes (where savings are expected to be achieved through productivity 
defaultand contractual savin
defaultgs) and transformational schemes such as service re-design and pathway changes. In 2013
default–14
default, the transformational schemes represent 44% of the total QIPP target for CCGs and direct commissioners (£0.9 billion). The latest data (from August) shows that £0.2 
defaultbillion (22% of the planned savings) had already been delivered and NHS England forecasts that £0.7 billion (78% of the planned savings) will be achieved by the end of the year. The shortfall on transformational schemes account for the vast majority of the
default total forecast QIPP shortfall. QIPP performance is measured against phased plans on a monthly basis as part of t
defaulthe NHS England finance report.
