default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultImprovements in workforce productivity are key to helping deliver the efficiency savings in t
defaulthis, and the next, spending round period. So far, workforce productivity gains have contributed 12% of the total savings made in 2011–12 and 2012–13, compared with 23% which has come from pay restraint. The workforce productivity share of total savings is 
defaultexpected to grow to 26% in 2013–14 and 2014–15. Despite improved productivity performance in the last two years, there still exists wide labour productivity variation at provider level. Levelling up performance as well as shifting the average provider perf
defaultormance upwards will help achieve the workforce produ
defaultctivity gains that are needed.
