defaultAcross health and care provision, services are often disjointed and poorly coordinated which causes distress for people who need care a
defaultnd support as well as their families and carers. Disjointed care leads to poor experiences, worse outcomes and inefficiencies across the system. In contrast, better coordinated care, focused on individuals rather than traditional service boundaries, has th
defaulte potential to improve services with positive impact on people’s experience, outcomes and on the efficiency of services.
default82
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, while there is broad consensus that integration has the potential to deliver large benefits, evidence as to the effectiveness 
defaultof specific schemes that the NHS and/or local authorities have put in place is, on the whole, weak. In this context, a policy of top-down reorganisation of services to fit a particular model of integrated care would be counter-productive. This is why the D
defaultepartment is committed to supporting health and social care organisations to work together to develop local models of integrated care that work for them, by removing barriers, sharing tools and innovations, and helping to build the evidence base of what wo
defaultrks locally.
default83
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
